In Lab 1, the innervation      of the body wall and limbs (“the container”) is considered. The innervation of viscera, including the heart, lungs and abdominal organs (“the contents”), will be considered in later labs
1.2   Innervation of “The Container”
to supply with neural input
innervation
Marker
Cutaneous innervation by dorsal rami

The targets of the nervous system in the body wall and limbs are threefold:
skeletal (voluntary) muscle, innervated by somatic motor neurons 
vascular      smooth (involuntary) muscle and both arrector pili muscle       and glands in the skin, innervated by visceral motor neurons of the ANS
sensory receptors in the skin, muscle and joints, innervated by sensory neurons
associated with blood vessels; vascular smooth muscle controls vascular resistance, and therefore blood flow to a region
vascular
Marker
smooth muscle that, when it contracts (involuntarily), makes your hair “stand on end”; think of a frightened cat
arrector pili
Marker

Dorsal and ventral rami, branching from spinal nerves, are mixed nerves containing all of these fibre types, and innervate all of these targets in the body wall and limbs.
Dorsal and ventral rami differ only in their distribution, not in their composition, i.e. they contain the same functional classes of neurons     .
Dorsal rami are smaller; they only innervate target tissues overlying, and adjacent to, the vertebral column (the para-axial      region).
Ventral rami are larger, and innervate target tissues in the remainder of the body wall and in the limbs, a much larger area of distribution necessitating a larger nerve.

Dorsal and ventral roots contain only sensory and motor axons, respectively.
Dorsal and ventral rami contain both motor and sensory axons.
Compare this with dorsal and ventral roots.
